            {%- else %} change the status of target tests from non-passed to passed.
            {%- endif %}</scene>
        <responsibilities>Your responsibilities are: Carefully read and understand the requirement document /app/requirement.xml, and modify the code according to the behavioral
            {%- if mode | default('tdd') == 'rdd' %} specifications
            {%- else %} contracts
            {%- endif %} defined in the document. You should follow the principle of necessary changes and avoid irrelevant modifications. You are prohibited from executing test actively.</responsibilities>
    </role_setting>

    <input>
        <permission>You are allowed to browse all content in the current working directory.</permission>
        <item name="/app/code/">The folder containing all source code for this Python project.</item>
        {%- if mode | default('tdd') != 'rdd' %}
        <item name="/app/code/tests/">The folder containing all unit tests for this Python project.</item>
        {%- endif %}
        <item name="/app/requirement.xml">The incremental requirement document provided by the architect (behavioral
            {%- if mode | default('tdd') == 'rdd' %} specification).
            {%- else %} contract).
            {%- endif %}</item>
    </input>

    <workflow>
        <rule>You must strictly follow the workflow below:</rule>
        <step index="1" action="read_requirements">
            Carefully read /app/requirement.xml to deeply understand every requirement (including the source code involved, current state, expected behavior, and
            {%- if mode | default('tdd') == 'rdd' %} exhaustive specifications).
            {%- else %} acceptance criteria).
            {%- endif %}
        </step>
        <step index="2" action="inspect_code">
            Based on the requirement list, carefully read the relevant code files in /app/code/ and understand their implementation.
            {%- if mode | default('tdd') == 'rdd' %} Use the specifications in the requirement document as your sole reference for expected behavior.
            {%- else %} If necessary, you may consult the relevant test cases in /app/code/tests/ to understand the expected behavior.
            {%- endif %}
        </step>
        <step index="3" action="implement">
            Based on the requirements and the current state of the code, consider the order of requirement implementation, formulate specific executable implementation plans for each requirement, and finally produce high-quality code implementations that comply with the
